<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-12-09T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-12-09T15:00:00-05:00" n="518" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d518">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">123 W 451/161: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Welles</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-12-09T15:00:00-05:00">December 9, 1933—3
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>140. Your 501, December 8, 11 a.m. The President asked me to say that
                                he believes it would be well for you to make your plans to leave on
                                the evening of the 12th or the 13th. Caffery is now at his home in
                                Louisiana and will presumably reach Habana a few days after your
                                departure. We all feel that it would be best for him not to give the
                                appearance of hastening to Habana immediately after you have
                                left.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>